File: AGENTS.md
L1- # Repository Guidelines
L2- 
L3- ## Project Structure & Module Organization
L4: `src/extension.ts` is the extension entrypoint and wires activation, commands, and views. `src/components/` contains UI-facing providers and panels such as the status bar item, checkpoint tree, and active session tree. `src/checkpoints/` holds the session/checkpoint domain logic, git enrichment, storage, transcript parsing, and search helpers. General utilities live in top-level `src/*.ts` files such as `workspaceProbe.ts` and `runCommand.ts`. Tests live under `src/test/`, with reusable checkpoint fixtures in `src/test/checkpoints/fixtures/`. `media/` stores extension icons. Treat `dist/` and `out/` as generated output.
L5- 
L6- ## Build, Test, and Development Commands
L7- - `pnpm compile`: run type-checking, ESLint, and the esbuild bundle into `dist/extension.js`.
L8- - `pnpm watch`: run esbuild watch mode and `tsc --watch` together for local development.
L9- - `pnpm check-types`: run strict TypeScript checks only.
L10- - `pnpm lint`: lint `src/` with the repository ESLint config.
L11- - `pnpm test`: compile tests, rebuild the extension, and run the VS Code test harness.
L12- - `pnpm package`: build the production bundle used for publishing.
L13- 
L14- ## Coding Style & Naming Conventions
L15- Use strict TypeScript and follow the existing code style: tabs for indentation, semicolons, and mostly single-quoted imports/strings. Use `PascalCase` for classes, providers, and exported types; use `camelCase` for functions and locals; use `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for extension-wide constants. Keep command and context identifiers namespaced, for example `session.bridge.entire.refresh`. Let ESLint catch small consistency issues, and do not hand-edit generated files in `dist/` or `out/`.
L16- 
L17- ## Testing Guidelines
L18- Write tests as `*.test.ts` under `src/test/`, mirroring the feature area when possible, such as `src/test/checkpoints/`. This project uses Mocha with `@vscode/test-cli` and `vscode-test`, compiling test files to `out/test/**/*.test.js`. Prefer fixture-backed tests for checkpoint parsing, git metadata joins, and tree/detail view models. No formal coverage threshold is configured, but every behavior change should include or update targeted tests.
L19- 
L20- ## Commit & Pull Request Guidelines
L21- Recent history uses short, imperative commit subjects, sometimes with lightweight prefixes such as `feat:` or `refactor:`. Keep each commit focused on one change and describe behavior, not process. Pull requests should summarize the user-visible effect, list verification commands run, link the relevant issue when applicable, and include screenshots or recordings for tree view, panel, or status bar changes.
L22- 
L23- ## Configuration Notes
L24- This extension targets VS Code `^1.105.0` and assumes an Entire-enabled Git repository at runtime. For tests and local development, prefer checked-in fixtures and mocks over machine-specific `.entire` state or hard-coded paths.
---
File: CONTRIBUTING.md
L1- # Contributing to Session Bridge
L2- 
L3- Thank you for your interest in contributing to Session Bridge! This guide will help you get started with the project and understand our development process.
L4- 
L5- ## Getting Started
L6- 
L7- ### Prerequisites
L8- 
L9- - [Node.js](https://nodejs.org/) (latest LTS recommended)
L10- - [pnpm](https://pnpm.io/) for package management
L11- - [VS Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/) for development
L12- - [Entire CLI](https://github.com/entireio/cli) (v0.5.5 or newer) installed on your system
L13- 
L14- ### Installation
L15- 
L16- 1. Clone the repository:
L17-    ```bash
L18-    git clone https://github.com/savekirk/session-bridge.git
L19-    cd session-bridge
L20-    ```
L21- 
L22- 2. Install dependencies:
L23-    ```bash
L24-    pnpm install
L25-    ```
L26- 
L27- ## Development Workflow
L28- 
L29- ### Build Commands
L30- 
L31- We use `pnpm` for all development tasks. Key scripts include:
L32- 
L33- - `pnpm compile`: Performs type-checking, linting, and bundles the extension into `dist/extension.js`.
L34- - `pnpm watch`: Runs esbuild and TypeScript in watch mode for local development.
L35- - `pnpm check-types`: Runs strict TypeScript checks only.
L36- - `pnpm lint`: Lints the `src/` directory using our ESLint configuration.
L37- - `pnpm package`: Builds the production bundle used for publishing.
L38- 
L39- ### Running the Extension Locally
L40- 
L41- 1. Open the project in VS Code.
L42- 2. Press `F5` or go to the "Run and Debug" view and select "Run Extension".
L43- 3. A new VS Code window (Extension Development Host) will open with the extension loaded.
L44- 
L45- ## Project Structure
L46- 
L47- - `src/extension.ts`: Extension entry point, command registration, and view wiring.
L48- - `src/components/`: UI-facing providers and panels (Status Bar, Tree Views, Panels).
L49- - `src/checkpoints/`: Core domain logic for sessions, checkpoints, Git enrichment, and storage.
L50- - `src/test/`: Test suites, mirrored to the source structure.
L51: - `media/`: Extension icons and demo assets.
L52- - `dist/` and `out/`: Generated build and test outputs (ignored by Git).
L53- 
L54- ## Coding Standards
L55- 
L56- We follow strict TypeScript and specific formatting conventions:
L57- 
L58- - **Indentation**: Use **tabs** for indentation.
L59- - **Quotes**: Use **single quotes** for imports and strings unless escaping is necessary.
L60- - **Semicolons**: Always use semicolons.
L61- - **Naming Conventions**:
L62-   - `PascalCase` for classes, providers, and exported types.
L63-   - `camelCase` for functions and local variables.
L64-   - `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for extension-wide constants.
L65- - **Namespacing**: Commands and context identifiers should be namespaced (e.g., `session.bridge.entire.refresh`).
L66- 
L67- ## Testing Guidelines
L68- 
L69- Every bug fix or new feature should include or update targeted tests.
L70- 
L71- - **Location**: Write tests as `*.test.ts` under `src/test/`, mirroring the `src/` structure.
L72- - **Framework**: We use Mocha with `@vscode/test-cli`.
L73- - **Running Tests**: Run `pnpm test` to compile tests, rebuild the extension, and execute the VS Code test harness.
L74- - **Fixtures**: Prefer fixture-backed tests for complex logic like checkpoint parsing or Git metadata joins. Existing fixtures are located in `src/test/checkpoints/fixtures/`.
L75- 
L76- ## Commit and Pull Request Guidelines
L77- 
L78- ### Commit Messages
L79- 
L80- - Use short, imperative subjects (e.g., `feat: add session search`).
L81- - Use lightweight prefixes like `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, or `docs:`.
L82- - Focus on the **why** of the change rather than the process.
L83- 
L84- ### Pull Requests
L85- 
L86- **Important**: Before starting work on any significant change or submitting a pull request, please open a [discussion](https://github.com/savekirk/session-bridge/discussions) or an [issue](https://github.com/savekirk/session-bridge/issues) to discuss your proposal. This helps ensure your contribution aligns with the project's direction and avoids wasted effort.
L87- 
L88- - Summarize the user-visible effect of the change.
L89- - List the verification steps or commands run.
L90- - Link relevant issues if applicable.
L91- - **UI Changes**: Include screenshots or recordings if the PR modifies tree views, panels, or the status bar.
L92- 
L93- ## Reporting Issues
L94- 
L95- Use the [GitHub Issues](https://github.com/savekirk/session-bridge/issues) page to report bugs or suggest features. When reporting a bug, please include:
L96- - A clear description of the issue.
L97- - Steps to reproduce.
L98- - Your OS and VS Code version.
L99- - Entire CLI version.
